ANGLO-INDIAN (MIS)RELATIONS AT ROANOKE

&lt;&lt;As the months passed, the Roanoke colonists began to starve. Trouble
with Pemisipan's Indians abated for a while due to the benevolence of
ENSENORE, Pemisipan's &quot;father,&quot; the &quot;only frend to our nation that we
had amongst them&quot;. Under ENSENORE's influence, Pemisipan ordered the
Weopomiok Indians to acknowledge Queen Elizabeth as their sovereign,
and the Indians henceforth aided the English in setting up houses
and growing food. Upon ENSENORE's death in April 1586, however, this
interlude of relative peace ended as Lane uncovered a plot by Pemisipan
and Okisko, king of the Weopomiok Indians, to assassinate him during
a nighttime raid. And although Menatonon and the Choanokes remained
&quot;more faithfull in their promises&quot;, their friendship was due in part
to coercion: Lane held Menatonon's son captive, threatening to kill
him when he tried to run away. [On June 1] Lane killed Pemisipan.

Eight days later, Francis Drake arrived with a fleet of 23 ships.
Following a major storm which destroyed a good part of the fleet, Lane
accepted Drake's offer for passage back to England. Fifteen men were
left behind, and they would continue to sour Anglo-Indian relations
in preparation for the next colony, which arrived in 1587. This 2nd
colony was led by John White, the artist, who was considerably less
inclined toward unprovoked violence. The colony had a shaky start,
however: when the settlers arrived in July 1587, they found no
trace of the 15 men, and Lane's fort had been razed by fire.&gt;&gt;
-------------------------------------------------------------

&lt;&lt;By 1586, Raleigh was already planning another colony in Virginia. This
one would be more ambitions, with its own coat of arms and the title,
&quot;Cittie of Ralegh.&quot; It would be agrarian rather than militaristic, less
an adventure than a commitment. Raleigh's decision to locate it on
the lower end of the Chesapeake Bay was prompted by Lane's report of
friendly Indians and a good natural harbor. The inclusion of 17 women
and 9 children among the 110 colonists would make this a long-term,
self-perpetuating settlement. Instead of wages, each settler was
deeded a 50-acre plot, thereby giving him a stake in the undertaking.
John White, the artist who had accompanied the first voyage,
was appointed Governor, to be aided by 12 assistants.

When the three ships sailed in May of 1587, the plan was to stop briefly
at Roanoke Island to resupply Grenville's party. But when they arrived
in July, the pilot Fernandez insisted that the summer was too far
advanced to go further, and the colonists were left at Roanoke.

In 1590, John White got passage on a privateering voyage.
As the party stepped ashore, there was no sign of the colonists
except the letters &quot;CRO&quot; carved on a tree. The houses had been
taken down and a palisade constructed, on one post of which
was carved &quot;CROATAN,&quot; but there was no Maltese cross.&gt;&gt;
