Okay, maybe I'm wrong, so let's consider this. It's
been stated that the phoenix was one of Elizabeth's symbols
or emblems. I didn't know that, but I'll accept it on face
value.

As well, Shakespeare himself used the phoenix in
connection with Elizabeth in &quot;Henry VIII&quot; (Act 5 Scene V)

In her days every man shall eat in safety
Under his own vine what he plants, and sing
The merry songs of peace to all his neighbours.
God shall be truly known; and those about her
From her shall read the perfect ways of honour,

And by those claim their greatness, not by blood.
Nor shall this peace sleep with her; but as when
The bird of wonder dies, the maiden phoenix
Her ashes new create another heir
As great in admiration as herself,
So shall she leave her blessedness to one-
When heaven shall call her from this cloud of darkness-
Who from the sacred ashes of her honour
Shall star-like rise, as great in fame as she was,
And so stand fix'd.

So it's certainly not impossible that the phoenix in
Sonnet 19 is a reference to Elizabeth.

But should we conclude that because the phoenix was
a symbol of Elizabeth, and because Shakespeare used the
phoenix in connection with a description of her, that in
Sonnet 19 he is also referring to her?

I don't know. Should we conclude that the phoenix
in &quot;The Phoenix and Turtle&quot; is a reference to Elizabeth?
Perhaps it was (I'm not that familiar with speculations on
this poem), but hasn't there been speculation that it
referred to other historical persons? If so, mightn't the
other person referred to in &quot;The Phoenix and Turtle&quot; also be
the person referred to in Sonnet 19?

For that matter, does the phoenix *have* to refer to
anyone in particular? Kerrigan glosses the passage as
follows:

&quot;Indeed, 'burn...in her blood' does more than describe a
painful death: it quibbles on the idiom 'to be in blood',
meaning 'to be in one's prime', to imply Time can kill the
phoenix whenever it wants.&quot; p. 198

Assuming Kerrigan is correct on his idioms, this is
a reasonable interpetation of the line which doesn't involve
any personal reference. And it works well for me - the paws
of the lion, the teeth of the tiger, the blood of the
phoenix.

Obviously, this doesn't preclude the *possibility*
that the phoenix was a reference to Elizabeth. It just
seems to me people are being a bit too quick to give the
idea more weight than it deserves.

