Under normal circumstances, no. We could take phoenix to mean phoenix and
nothing else. But, looking for a &quot;straight&quot; reading in Sonnet 19, we run
into a very awkward line - &quot;burn...in her blood&quot; - which is ostensibly a
mixed metaphor. We have another example of a mixed metaphor in &quot;take arms
against a sea of troubles&quot;. Either we say that it's a bad line, something
bad enough that we think Shakespeare is unlikely to have written it, or else
we say it's a reference to an event within recent memory - the defeat of
the Armada - which mitigates its clumsiness. In terms of the &quot;straight&quot;
reading of Sonnet 19, there is nothing to be done with &quot;in her blood&quot; except
throw a blanket over it. No retelling of the phoenix myth that I've come
across makes reference to blood at all. It is not something normally
associated with a phoenix. That's the poet's first doubtful move -
incorporating material that is out of place. His second is to tie it to
&quot;burn&quot; closely enough that the effect is nearly ludicrous. So basically you
take your choice - either it was one of the poet's off-days, or else it has
some other meaning that to some extent legitimises the wording.

At the moment I'm inclined to the latter course, but it isn't crucial to
the reading of the sonnet as a whole, and doesn't bend its meaning in any
way. It's a passing reference in a sonnet that is otherwise not about her,
and certainly not addressed to her. But it is not an inappropriate
reference. When you are considering the passage of time, and the things that
are subject to it, the monarchy is one example you might think of,
especially when the present incumbent is &quot;long-lived&quot; (more than thirty
