We can't imagine a man with a sword doing much ending with oceans. Without
the Armada reference, we'd have to say it was ill-chosen. So I'd say the
Armada was a lot more relevant than an ocean would be to the meaning of the
line, since it is at least beatable. And topical too, even after 12 years.
It was an event that would not easily slip from the memory. The defeat of
the Armada was the pivotal military event of that period of English history,
the equivalent of Trafalgar in the nineteenth century, or the Battle of
Britain in the twentieth. It was a win that went against the general
current.

